<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900521-0002</DOCNO><DOCID>900521-0002.</DOCID><HL>   Bank of Italy Key Rate   Cut One Point to 12.5%   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>05/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   EUROP</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><LP>   MILAN, Italy -- The discount rate at the Bank of Italy,the central bank, was reduced one full percentage point to12.5%, effective today, in a move aimed at restoringstability to the European Monetary System, the treasury said.   The treasury cited development of the Italian economy andthe ad hoc budget-deficit reduction package approved by thegovernment on Friday.</LP><TEXT>   It was the first time the discount rate -- the interestrate at which the Bank of Italy lends funds to commercialbanks -- was changed since March 3, 1989, when the centralbank's key rate was raised to 13.5% from 12.5%. Thus, it is apivotal indicator of the central bank's monetary policy andwill help commercial banks set their lending rates to thepublic. Under Italian law, the treasury decides on changes inthe discount rate, following a recommendation by the Bank ofItaly governor.   The move didn't surprise financial markets, though manymoney-market operators had believed the Bank of Italy wouldwait until June before easing its monetary stance.   The government approved an emergency package of spendingcuts and new revenue measures that will reduce the 1990budget deficit by 11.75 trillion lire ($9.68 billion) to 136trillion lire.   The treasury said the entry of the lira into the narrow,2.25% band in the European Monetary System in Januarytriggered a large inflow of foreign capital, which had&quot;pushed the lira to its upper limit {in the EMS}, despiteconspicuous&quot; interventions by the Bank of Italy. The liracontinued to strengthen, despite a cut in short-term interestrates this year, which narrowed Italy's interest-ratedifferential with other European countries.</TEXT></DOC>